narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Similar to calc that I took in high school but more in-depth about concepts I'd already learned

I felt like I had a deeper understanding of the math concepts that were taught in this class. Although I learned a lot of this stuff in high school, I believe the education was very superficial. I felt that I was being consistently challenged, and it really helped to change my perspective on the amount of time and effort I put into learning the key concepts. I found myself having to learn how each topic interacted and connected with other ones within the course. Overall, I felt the most challenged in this course and I enjoyed it the most out of all my courses.
Intro to logarithmic functions, graphing of rational functions, optimization, derivate rules, natural log properties, etc.
In the duration of this course, I more finely tuned my mathematical skills.
A good and thorough foundation in calculus: derivatives, linear approximation, optimization.
Critical thinking.

I learned a lot about doing math effectively -- doing problems that best suited what I needed to learn and would help me practice all skills. This class also taught me a lot about budgeting time! ULA hours and workshops and peer tutoring were all huge parts of my weekly time commitment.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: offer more one on one tutoring please!!! I'm a student athlete, I do not have time to sit in ULA office hours every day for multiple hours for homework help. ULA office hours are also often overcrowded and difficult for students to get help
I believe that ULAs are the best thing that has ever happened to me. They are such a big reason why I was able to fully digest concepts and finish my psets.
Material being assigned prior to class helped provide a overview of what we would be practicing and most of time during class was doing problems which would help us work on the skills being taught.
The strengths of this course include how the material is taught, and many of the resources made available.
Theres a huge amount of support for this course and its well structured. Individual sections vary from professor to professor.
All the different assignments were varying in difficulty.

Great resources -- ULA office hours 4x a week (now changed to 6x a week for Math 111), accessible professors, lots of communication fostered with peers in class, peer tutoring at no cost to the student.
Weaknesses -- textbook is not great at explaining topics, the first midterm was harshly graded and resulted in lots of points taken off for carry-over errors, and the jump in the 3rd week from easy algebra concepts to precalculus was jarring.
Overall a good class, but the weaknesses were stressful.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes if you need to take it

I would absolutely recommend this course to another student. I felt that I grew a lot as a student in this course. It not only consistently challenged me, but it helped me create fortified relationships with my peers and tutors. It felt like a community that I was comfortable approaching when I was having difficulty with concepts and it created a very conducive learning environment.
I would recommend this course to other students making th transition from high school calculus to college.
I would very much recommend this course to other students. The instructors care a lot about the students' learning and the ULA drop-in hours are very helpful.
Yes, I think it is a great starter mathematics course that students should take if they find quantitative reasoning and/or mathematics interesting.
Would recommend if you NEED calculus, but there may be better QR options for you personally.

Not if you do not have to take a math. If you do, I would definitely recommend this over 112. That said, though it is a well-structured class with wonderful professors, definitely consider time commitments. Prior evaluations do not note the mandatory 1-hour weekly dedication to a workshop, the ULA hours in the evenings you will want to go to every once in a while (they are helpful!!), office hours you will also find yourself attending here and there, and potential 1-hour dedication to a peer tutoring session. I enjoyed what I learned as a student who hadn't previously taken calc, but definitely just consider the time outside of the classroom.
